arch:property.oc:show_val: Although it is supposed to represent the burnt floor level below 3545, in fact the material clearly forms a single depositional unit. Refits of modern breaks across the units were recorded with 3545. 3548 is a small unit, mostly burnt at low temperatures. It includes the tip of a cattle horn core with high temperature burning, probably associated with the pile of horn cores in 2210. Mostly skull and horn core crumbles, probably mostly cattle. A sheep/goat mandible and some tooth fragments, some sheep-size long bone fragments, and some fragmentary large mammal burnt ribs account for most of the rest. Sample 1 flotation >4 mm sorted 100%, recorded completely. Similar to dry-sieved material: much burnt, mostly little crumbles. A little foot here: a sheep/goat metatarsal and a burnt digested sesamoid and phalanx (from different animals). These last suggest some dog poop was in the deposit before it burned; perhaps redeposited, as not much digestion. 2003: Found another small bag. This one has a wider range of body parts, about half of it burnt. There are sheep-size long bone and rib fragments, and a few large mammal rib bits; a small pile of crumbled unburnt cattle horn core; a couple of long bones, some sheep-size skull, and a young pig mandible. This set, perhaps from lower down, seems a little more varied. Last number = 108

arch:string.div: The unique identifier for each contextual unit, matching those used in the central Çatalhöyük excavation database and in publications. The excavation uses single-context recording.
